{"schema":"algviz/1","title":"Add and Search Word (wildcard)","topic":"tries","code":["public void AddWord(string word)","{","    TrieNode node = _root;","    foreach (char c in word)","    {","        int i = c - 'a';","        node.Children[i] ??= new TrieNode();","        node = node.Children[i]!;","    }","    node.IsEnd = true;","}","","public bool Search(string word) => Dfs(word, 0, _root);","","private bool Dfs(string word, int idx, TrieNode node)","{","    if (idx == word.Length) return node.IsEnd;","    char c = word[idx];","    if (c == '.')","    {","        foreach (TrieNode? child in node.Children)","            if (child is not null && Dfs(word, idx + 1, child))","                return true;","        return false;","    }","    TrieNode? next = node.Children[c - 'a'];","    return next is not null && Dfs(word, idx + 1, next);","}"],"structures":{"trie":{"type":"graph","label":"trie (edge = next char; * = word end)"},"pat":{"type":"array1d","label":"Search pattern (\".\" = any child)"}},"frames":[{"line":13,"caption":"Stored words {bad, dad, mad} in a trie; now Search(\".ad\") where \".\" matches ANY single character.","note":"A trie keys a tree by characters: each edge is one letter and the path from the root spells a prefix. AddWord is plain insert; the interesting part is that Search may carry `.` wildcards. A literal walk cannot handle a `.` — at that position you do not know which edge to take — so Search becomes a DFS that branches into every child on a dot. We first build the three words, then run the dotted search.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86}],"edges":[]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"."},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":10,"caption":"AddWord(\"bad\"): walk b→a→d creating each missing node, then set IsEnd on the last → \"bad\" is stored.","note":"AddWord is the ordinary trie insert — no wildcards ever appear in STORED words, only in queries. Each character follows a child edge, creating the node when the edge is missing (`Children[i] ??= new TrieNode()`), and the final node gets `IsEnd = true`. Here bad, dad, mad share no prefix, so each gets its own b/d/m branch; the structure is three parallel `?-a-d` paths.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","added":"bad"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"frontier"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"."},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":10,"caption":"AddWord(\"dad\"): walk b→a→d creating each missing node, then set IsEnd on the last → \"dad\" is stored.","note":"AddWord is the ordinary trie insert — no wildcards ever appear in STORED words, only in queries. Each character follows a child edge, creating the node when the edge is missing (`Children[i] ??= new TrieNode()`), and the final node gets `IsEnd = true`. Here bad, dad, mad share no prefix, so each gets its own b/d/m branch; the structure is three parallel `?-a-d` paths.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","added":"dad"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"match"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"frontier"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"."},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":10,"caption":"AddWord(\"mad\"): walk b→a→d creating each missing node, then set IsEnd on the last → \"mad\" is stored.","note":"AddWord is the ordinary trie insert — no wildcards ever appear in STORED words, only in queries. Each character follows a child edge, creating the node when the edge is missing (`Children[i] ??= new TrieNode()`), and the final node gets `IsEnd = true`. Here bad, dad, mad share no prefix, so each gets its own b/d/m branch; the structure is three parallel `?-a-d` paths.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","added":"mad"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"match"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"m","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"m","to":"ma","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"ma","to":"mad","highlight":"frontier"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"."},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":11,"caption":"All three words inserted. They share no prefix, so the trie is three parallel branches b-a-d, d-a-d, m-a-d.","note":"Worst case a trie has 1 + (total characters) nodes; shared prefixes collapse common heads into one path. Here bad/dad/mad share nothing, so each gets its own full branch — and that is exactly why the leading dot in \".ad\" will have to fork into all three first-letter children.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"m","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"m","to":"ma","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ma","to":"mad","highlight":"muted"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":"."},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":19,"caption":"Dfs(idx=0, node=root): the pattern char is \".\", a wildcard.","note":"This is the whole trick of LC 211. On a literal you would take the ONE matching edge, but on a `.` you do not know which letter the word had — so the search forks into EVERY present child and succeeds if ANY branch matches. That fork is a depth-first search: try child b first, recurse the rest of the pattern down it, and only if it fails fall back to d, then m. A `.` multiplies the work by the branching factor (≤ 26), which is why search is O(26^d · L) for d dots — but it only ever descends edges that actually exist.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","idx":0,"node":"root","word[idx]":"'.'"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"m","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"m","to":"ma","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ma","to":"mad","highlight":"muted"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":".","pointers":["idx"],"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":21,"caption":"\".\" branches the DFS into EVERY existing child of root: {b, d, m}. Try them in order; succeed if any matches.","note":"This is the whole trick of LC 211. On a literal you would take the ONE matching edge, but on a `.` you do not know which letter the word had — so the search forks into EVERY present child and succeeds if ANY branch matches. That fork is a depth-first search: try child b first, recurse the rest of the pattern down it, and only if it fails fall back to d, then m. A `.` multiplies the work by the branching factor (≤ 26), which is why search is O(26^d · L) for d dots — but it only ever descends edges that actually exist.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","idx":0,"node":"root","word[idx]":"'.'","children":"{b, d, m}"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"m","highlight":"frontier"},{"from":"m","to":"ma","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ma","to":"mad","highlight":"muted"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":".","pointers":["idx"],"highlight":"frontier"},{"key":"c1","value":"a"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":27,"caption":"Branch b → Dfs(idx=1, node=b). Pattern char is the literal \"a\": take the one matching edge.","note":"Back to a literal character inside the b-branch: no branching here. We take the single edge `Children[c-'a']`; if it is missing this branch dies and returns false, and the DFS backtracks to try the next child of the dot. The edge exists (b has an `a` child), so we descend and advance idx by one — the literal walk is plain O(1) per step.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","idx":1,"node":"'b'","word[idx]":"'a'","branch":"b"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"current"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ba","to":"bad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"d","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"d","to":"da","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"da","to":"dad","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"root","to":"m","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"m","to":"ma","highlight":"muted"},{"from":"ma","to":"mad","highlight":"muted"}]},"pat":{"type":"array1d","cells":[{"key":"c0","value":".","pointers":[]},{"key":"c1","value":"a","pointers":["idx"],"highlight":"active"},{"key":"c2","value":"d"}],"range":null}}},{"line":27,"caption":"Edge \"a\" exists under b → descend to node \"ba\". Next pattern char is the literal \"d\".","note":"Back to a literal character inside the b-branch: no branching here. We take the single edge `Children[c-'a']`; if it is missing this branch dies and returns false, and the DFS backtracks to try the next child of the dot. The edge exists (b has an `a` child), so we descend and advance idx by one — the literal walk is plain O(1) per step.","vars":{"stored":"[bad, dad, mad]","query":".ad","idx":2,"node":"'ba'","word[idx]":"'d'","branch":"b"},"result":null,"states":{"trie":{"type":"graph","directed":true,"nodes":[{"key":"root","value":"root","x":50,"y":8,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"b","value":"b","x":20,"y":34,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"d","value":"d","x":50,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"m","value":"m","x":80,"y":34,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ba","value":"a","x":20,"y":60,"highlight":"current"},{"key":"da","value":"a","x":50,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"ma","value":"a","x":80,"y":60,"highlight":"muted"},{"key":"bad","value":"bad*","x":20,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"dad","value":"dad*","x":50,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"},{"key":"mad","value":"mad*","x":80,"y":86,"highlight":"visited"}],"edges":[{"from":"root","to":"b","highlight":"current"},{"from":"b","to":"ba","highlight":"current"},{"from":"ba"